	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">The Flood</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sparrow">Sparrow</a></li><li><a href="/issues/362">February 2006</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><em>Several months before Hurricane Katrina flooded New Orleans, spring storms caused major flooding throughout the Catskill Mountains in New York. The Esopus River Valley was among the hardest-hit areas, with bridges rendered impassable and parts of the town of Phoenicia left underwater.</em></p>

<p class="text-right"><em>&mdash; Ed.</em></p>

<h6>APRIL 2, 2005<br />
PHOENICIA, NEW YORK</h6>

<p>I am at my neighbor Rachel&rsquo;s house, because my own house is flooded &mdash; or, at least, I <em>think</em> it&rsquo;s flooded.</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s difficult to remember the sequence of events that led us here. Everything came so quickly. The first warning was when Perdita called, saying, &ldquo;I hear they are evacuating people from Phoenicia.&rdquo; Heavy rains and spring thaw were causing the Esopus River to overflow its banks.</p>

<p>Almost every night this week I&rsquo;ve been dreaming I&rsquo;m homeless, moving into a new apartment in a strange city. Perhaps my dreams were preparing me for this!</p>

<p>Next, Rachel phoned. She had called the police, who had advised her to &ldquo;seek higher ground.&rdquo;</p>

<p>This is almost religious advice.</p>

<p>I began to hear, in my mind, Stevie Wonder sing: &ldquo;Gonna keep on trying / Till I reach the highest ground.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Our thirteen-year-old daughter, Sylvia, was sleeping over at a friend&rsquo;s house. As my wife, Violet, and I decided whether to evacuate, I absurdly made dal, an Indian soup of red lentils. First I saut&eacute;ed seeds of mustard, cumin, and fennel. Then I added chopped red cabbage. Finally I washed the red lentils and poured them in the pot, stirring everything with a wooden spoon.</p>

<p>While the soup cooked, I called the police. They offered to send a boat for us. I told them I had to discuss it with my wife.</p>

<p>My last glimpse of our home was like a scene from a horror movie. Water poured into the garage &mdash; muddy brown water at least five inches deep. This vision was impossible, a violation of my ordinary domestic life, like the moment the first zombie smashes his hand through the wooden door in <em>Night of the Living Dead</em>.</p>

<p>Somehow I&rsquo;d expected the river to stop before entering our house, simply out of riverine politeness. But the river can&rsquo;t even see our house. The river is blind, like an arm with no eyes.</p>

<p>Just before we left, Violet put Bananacake, our rabbit, in the bathtub.</p>

<p>Violet and I walked through the woods to Rachel&rsquo;s. Our next-door neighbors Buddy and Betty traveled with us, in the darkness and rain.</p>

<p>Betty offered to carry my bags for me. They were slowing me down quite a bit, so I agreed. Then, when we got to Rachel&rsquo;s, the police were parked in her driveway. Betty walked off, still carrying my bags. A police car drove her away.</p>

<p>Here is what I own for certain, right now:</p>

<pre class="text-indent"><span class="poem-line">one pair of black pants</span>
<span class="poem-line">two socks</span>
<span class="poem-line">one handkerchief</span>
<span class="poem-line">two pens</span>
<span class="poem-line">one undershirt</span>
<span class="poem-line">one long-sleeved blue shirt</span>
<span class="poem-line">my wallet</span>
<span class="poem-line">a pair of gloves</span>
<span class="poem-line">a scarf</span>
<span class="poem-line">a wool hat</span>
<span class="poem-line">a pair of fishing boots</span>
<span class="poem-line">a big umbrella</span></pre>

<p>Here is what I possibly own (if Betty hasn&rsquo;t lost it):</p>

<pre class="text-indent"><span class="poem-line">one loaf of whole-wheat bread</span>
<span class="poem-line">several slices of pumpernickel bread</span>
<span class="poem-line">a bag of puffed rice</span>
<span class="poem-line">a few rye crackers</span>
<span class="poem-line">a container of tahini</span>
<span class="poem-line"><em>A Passage to India</em>, by E.M. Forster</span>
<span class="poem-line"><em>The Dark Kingdom</em>, by Kenneth Patchen</span>
<span class="poem-line"><em>The Man without a Country and Other Tales</em>, by Edward Everett Hale</span>
<span class="poem-line">a container of toothpaste</span>
<span class="poem-line">dental floss</span>
<span class="poem-line">two toothbrushes</span>
<span class="poem-line">a dental stimulator</span>
<span class="poem-line">two plastic bags</span></pre>

<p>I was famished earlier, but once I realized my food was gone, I was suddenly no longer hungry. Rachel kindly offered us walnut-and-broccoli polenta with tomato sauce, but I decided not to eat. If I have lost everything I own, I might as well lose some weight as well.</p>

<p>I am on the Flood Diet.</p>

<p>When we bought our house two years ago, we knew it was on a &ldquo;hundred-year flood plain.&rdquo; I guess we hoped a flood would wait a hundred years to come.</p>

<p>As Rachel was brushing her teeth just now, she exclaimed, &ldquo;Oh, my God! I can see High Street from my window. High Street is a <em>river</em>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I looked out the window. Faintly I could see water flowing, reflecting the streetlights.</p>

<p>Riddle: If a street is a river, what is a house?</p>

<p>Answer: A boat.</p>

<p>In Mark Twain&rsquo;s <em>Huckleberry Finn</em>, Huck and Jim see a house floating down the Mississippi River. The chapter is titled &ldquo;The House of Death Floats By.&rdquo; Here is the moment that they find the house:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>Another night when we was up at the head of the island, just before daylight, here comes a frame house down, on the west side. She was a two-story, and tilted over considerable. We paddled out and got aboard &mdash; clumb in an upstairs window. But it was too dark to see yet, so we made the canoe fast and set in her to wait for daylight.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I think of Bananacake, our rabbit. Certainly she is shitting in my bathtub. Or is she drowning by now? Or floating in the bathtub down the river?</p>

<p>We don&rsquo;t know if the water entered our house. When we left, it was up to the top step in front.</p>

<p>Soon after we arrived at Rachel&rsquo;s, Violet said, &ldquo;I wish I had brought the crossword puzzle!&rdquo; (Lately, we&rsquo;ve been doing crossword puzzles together.)</p>

<p>I find myself worrying about particular papers we left behind. Are my passport and my wife&rsquo;s passport and our daughter&rsquo;s floating in the Esopus? What about the check Violet wrote to Doe to pay her back for the tickets to Universal Studios? Has that floated away?</p>

<p>At Universal Studios last week, my family went on the Twister ride. You stand in a small Midwestern town &mdash; or a mock-up thereof &mdash; and a tornado hits. Lightning shatters a tree in front of you. A sign from a gas station falls. The sewer system bursts into flame. Then a cow comes flying through the air, mooing boisterously. The ride is simultaneously silly and scary.</p>

<p>But you never consider, at any time, that actual people suffer in a disaster.</p>

<p>I will <em>not</em> make a bargain with God: &ldquo;If you spare my daughter&rsquo;s room, I will volunteer at a home for the blind.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Why didn&rsquo;t I pick up the laptop from the floor and put it on a table? I ask myself this question forty times. That action would have taken four seconds and saved a thousand dollars.</p>

<p>A week ago we saw the stage version of <em>The Diary of Anne Frank</em> in Orlando, Florida. Now we are living at a neighbor&rsquo;s house, just like Anne Frank. Anne was fleeing fascism; we are fleeing a flood. The two are similar: a swift, unexpected fury.</p>

<p>I hear the roar of the river outside. It sounds like a waterfall. But the water is not falling; it is rushing. It is a waterrush.</p>

<p>Most of this water is melted snow from the mountains, I remind myself. I am hearing the sound of raging, roaring snow.</p>

<p>All sorts of theological thoughts enter my mind. For example: I am being punished for my lack of compassion for the victims of the tsunami.</p>

<p><em>I am fleeing a flood</em>, I think. I am like the people one sees on <span class="smallcaps">TV</span>, who all seem so interchangeable and predictable. &ldquo;The water just kept rising, and suddenly we were under,&rdquo; they say, or some such obvious remark. What is the term for such people? &ldquo;Flood victims.&rdquo; That is me: a &ldquo;flood victim.&rdquo;</p>

<p>A flood should last one day, it seems to me. In my mind, a flood is a day&rsquo;s event. But what if the flood doesn&rsquo;t agree? What if the flood wants to last four days &mdash; or a month?</p>

<p>I imagine myself entering my house: It is filled with water, like an aquarium. I am swimming through my living room with big, funny strokes, like Jerry Lewis in some movie I saw as a kid.</p>

<p>There are four possible outcomes: (1) the house is unhurt; (2) the house is partly filled with water; (3) the house is completely filled with water; (4) the house is gone.</p>

<p>Wondering which is true keeps me awake.</p>

<p>Is there a chance we will get rich from all this &mdash; from the flood insurance? Or will we lose everything, so that I will need to get a regular job?</p>

<p>These two fates are dangled before me.</p>

<p>My entire literary output is on two black computer disks on the top shelf of the pink desk in our home office. If these two disks can be retrieved, I will have everything I have written since 1990 &mdash; except for a few files I have not yet backed up, which now torment me.</p>

<p>But will these disks function if they have been underwater? And if the house is gone, of course, they are gone, too.</p>

<p>The disks are like the black box one searches for after an airplane crash.</p>

<p>My father likes to tell a joke about three retired Jews sitting in Miami Beach. They are explaining why they moved to Florida. One says, &ldquo;I had a small department store in Cincinnati, but unfortunately there was a fire. I collected the insurance money and moved to Florida.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The second one says, &ldquo;I had a dry-goods store in Omaha. One night there was a terrible fire. I took the insurance money and moved to Florida.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The third one says, &ldquo;I had a children&rsquo;s-clothing store in Wichita. One day we had a flood. After I got the insurance money, I moved to Florida.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The first two look at the third one for a long time. Finally, one asks, &ldquo;How do you start a flood?&rdquo;</p>

<h6>APRIL 3</h6>

<p>We are back in our house. The river stopped at our top step. Not one drop of water entered the house.</p>

<p>Bananacake is unharmed, though she did shit in the tub.</p>

<p>Our garage, of course, is flooded.</p>

<p>Betty and Buddy came by earlier with my bags and their apologies. She showed us photographs she had taken on her digital camera: a caboose fallen over on the railroad tracks; Fox Hollow Road underwater.</p>

<p>They said that the river rose three feet in fifteen minutes. Betty&rsquo;s car, which was parked in the driveway we share with them, was destroyed.</p>

<p>People are walking by with their dogs, entertaining themselves by gawking at the devastation. Is this an American trait, or does every nationality have such cheerful curiosity?</p>

<p>We were so busy being flooded, we didn&rsquo;t hear that the pope had died.</p>

<h6>APRIL 4</h6>

<p>Now we are in the &ldquo;after the flood&rdquo; period. A pair of women&rsquo;s panties hangs from a fallen tree in our backyard. At least they <em>look</em> like women&rsquo;s panties. I must go out back and research.</p>

<p>The water that comes out of the faucet is brownish red. This makes me nervous. I&rsquo;ve heard of people getting diseases (cholera?) after a flood, because the water is tainted. Although filtering the water makes it clear, I still believe we should boil it. At the moment I&rsquo;m boiling a pot of water. But how long should one boil water? I forget.</p>

<p>I want to find in the Bible God&rsquo;s beautiful promise to Noah and his family after the Flood. It is summarized in the spiritual &ldquo;Oh, Mary, Don&rsquo;t You Weep&rdquo;: &ldquo;God gave Noah the rainbow sign / No more water, the fire next time.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Apparently God was lying, because there are still floods.</p>

<p>Also, we must begin to make progress drying out the garage. I am worried that diseases breed in standing water, but I can&rsquo;t act until we hear from the insurance gods &mdash; and my wife, whose job it is to call them, is currently across the street, staring at the wreckage.</p>

<p>I take a bath in the bathtub. The water is so brown, I feel like I&rsquo;m back in India. In Calcutta I saw people bathing in muddy water. Somehow they emerged extremely clean.</p>

<h6>2 P.M. THE SAME DAY</h6>

<p>My wife called her father, who is also our insurance agent. He says we have a three-thousand-dollar deductible on the flood insurance. We will not become rich from this flood.</p>

<p>I keep stacks of magazines in the garage. A list of those destroyed by the flood: <em>Salonika</em>, <em>Spit</em>, <em>Sink Full of Dishes</em>, <em>Unbearables Assembling Magazine #6</em>, <em>Uno Mas</em>. (These are mostly magazines in which I have been published.)</p>

<p>I always thought that in a flood the water rose very slowly. This one was rampaging and thunderous. Perhaps ours was a &ldquo;flash flood.&rdquo; Perhaps there are seventeen types of floods.</p>

<p>Perhaps no two floods are alike &mdash; in their speed, or in any other way.</p>

<p>I located the Bible quote, Genesis 9:8-11:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>And God spoke unto Noah, and to his sons with him, saying,</p>

<p>And I, behold, I establish my covenant with you, and with your seed and after you;</p>

<p>And with every living creature that is with you, of the fowl, of the cattle, and of every beast of the earth with you; from all that go out of the ark, to every beast of the earth.</p>

<p>And I will establish my covenant with you; neither shall all flesh be cut off any more by the waters of a flood; neither shall there any more be a flood to destroy the earth.</p>
</blockquote>

<h6>APRIL 5</h6>

<p>I had trouble getting to sleep last night and woke up late today. This morning was sunny and bright: a perfect day to air out the garage.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I think we should open the garage door,&rdquo; I said to Violet.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I already did that!&rdquo; she snapped. Then she paused. &ldquo;I feel like every time you say something to me, I shout at you,&rdquo; she admitted. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry.&rdquo; Then she began to cry. &ldquo;I feel so overwhelmed.&rdquo;</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s like being the victim of abuse, to be in a flood. It&rsquo;s like your father hitting you. But it&rsquo;s not your father; it&rsquo;s a body of water. Or God.</p>

<p>A flood is an &ldquo;act of God.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I called the Shandaken Town Hall, to find out about the <span class="smallcaps">FEMA</span> money. &ldquo;First the president must declare this a disaster area,&rdquo; the fellow on the phone said. But he implied that the president was leaning toward this verdict.</p>

<p>I took a walk down Jay Street, where all the basements were flooded. In front of each house was a big pile of basement items drying in the sun: backpacks, flowerpots, hoses, books. Jay Street looked like a series of waterlogged garage sales.</p>

<p>In our flooded garage was a valise of clippings from my literary career: two of my Op-Ed pieces from the <em>New York Times</em>, the time I was quoted in <em>Vogue</em>, my two letters in the <em>New York Daily News</em>, many essays in the <em>New York Observer</em> &mdash; all soaked. I have begun to regard this as my greatest loss.</p>

<p>Today I began drying out some of the newspaper pages on the deck. They dry quickly but become completely rumpled, and are stained with mud.</p>

<p>Why did I entrust my thoughts to the delicate, fragile medium of paper? Fire burns it; water soaks it; in time it simply crumbles. In the future, I will write on brass plates.</p>

<h6>APRIL 7</h6>

<p>My daughter, Sylvia, is largely unaffected by this flood. She was a little nervous at first; she asked, &ldquo;Will it flood again?&rdquo; (a question for which, as for most questions posed by youths, we had no real answer). But the fact that nearly every artifact from her early childhood was coated with mud and utterly soaked didn&rsquo;t disturb her. &ldquo;Just throw it out,&rdquo; quoth Sylvia.</p>

<p>I, on the other hand, am shocked by every issue of <em>Musea</em> I have lost. Magazines I never really wanted to read now seem irreplaceable.</p>

<p>Today I received this quote by e-mail:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>Whatever is not yours, abandon it. When you have abandoned it, that will lead to your welfare and happiness.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
<p class="text-right">&mdash; the Buddha</p>
</blockquote>

<h6>APRIL 10</h6>

<p>There is something distinctly upside down about the Phoenicia landscape, even now. Across the road, where two men lived in trailers, a pair of sheds were tossed like dice. They still stand upended. Many trees are sideways, their long, luxurious roots stretched in the sunlight.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve finished drying all my record albums and most of the clippings from my literary career. The day was bright, sunny, and breezy &mdash; perfect for drying documents.</p>

<p>As the cardboard album covers dry, they warp, ripple, and expand. <em>Autumn in New York: The Guitar Artistry of Tal Farlow</em> is now the width of seven record albums. Similarly, the magazine <em>Inverted Ostrich: Newsletter of Social Commentary</em> (No. 3, July 1991) &mdash; which consists of four pages, each printed only on one side &mdash; is as thick as a twenty-one-page manuscript.</p>

<p>This is how the Universe works: after a flood, you have fewer possessions, but they fill the same amount of space.</p>

<h6>APRIL 11</h6>

<p>I spoke to Buddy today, out by the wall. He has to dig out all the silt that was deposited under his house. &ldquo;It isn&rsquo;t fun,&rdquo; he admitted.</p>

<p>He had called some government office in Kingston, which had told him we were unlikely to get any <span class="smallcaps">FEMA</span> money.</p>

<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s <span class="smallcaps">OK</span>,&rdquo; Buddy said. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a Vietnam vet; I&rsquo;m used to getting screwed by the government.&rdquo;</p>

<h6>APRIL 12</h6>

<p>Today I wrote the following poem. Afterward I realized: <em>This is about the flood</em>.</p>

<h5>Spiritual Poem</h5>

<pre class="text-indent"><span class="poem-line">As my ego</span>
<span class="poem-line">grows smaller,</span>
<span class="poem-line">there are fewer letters</span>
<span class="poem-line">in my name.</span></pre>

<p class="text-indent">&mdash; S ar ow</p>

<p>The flood washed away part of my name. But I am learning to accept this loss, to spell my name with fewer letters.</p>
														</div>


				
