			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1635">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In his essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/259/">The Flood</a>&rdquo; [February 2006] Sparrow tells an anti-Semitic joke that suggests that Jews are arsonists who have no qualms about defrauding insurance companies. Granted, he is only repeating a joke that his father once told, and even then it is only a joke. But the telling of this joke adds absolutely nothing to the content of the essay and is clearly a jab at a religion that Sparrow holds in disdain.</p>

<p>There is no room in <em>The Sun</em> for intolerance, religious or otherwise. Free speech should include a wide latitude of thought, but intolerant viewpoints do not deserve a voice.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jesús Galaviz<br>Fort Worth, Texas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1636">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was shocked to find an anti-Semitic joke in Sparrow&rsquo;s &ldquo;The Flood.&rdquo; It is precisely this kind of &ldquo;humor&rdquo; that perpetuates stereotypes of Jewish people as being dishonest and devious. I would have thought a magazine that promotes itself as being progressive and all-inclusive would have edited such a joke out of the essay.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Annette Star Lustgarten<br>Sedona, Arizona</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1637">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>While Sparrow managed in &ldquo;The Flood&rdquo; to cart away several bags of things from the rising waters that threatened his home, I was horrified that he abandoned his rabbit, a sentient being incapable of swimming, to a potentially terrifying death.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Name Withheld<br></p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1638">
								<p><a href="/contributors/sparrow"><strong>Sparrow</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>I must say that I never expected, in my long life, to be attacked as an anti-Semite by one person named Jes&uacute;s and another named Lustgarten. My only (feeble) defense is: I&rsquo;m Jewish.</p>

<p>As for Name Withheld, I agree with her (or him). It was morally wrong to abandon Bananacake, our rabbit.</p>

<p class="text-right">Guiltily,<br />
Sparrow</p>
	</div>


								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1064">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In the <a href="/issues/365/correspondence">May Correspondence</a>, Jes&uacute;s Galaviz states, &ldquo;There is no room in <em>The Sun</em> for intolerance, religious or otherwise. Free speech should include a wide latitude of thought, but intolerant viewpoints do not deserve a voice.&rdquo;</p>

<p>To say that any viewpoint &ldquo;does not deserve a voice&rdquo; seems rather intolerant to me. Galaviz&rsquo;s letter reminds me that sensitive and caring groups and individuals can also be intolerant.</p>

<p>I, for one, am glad <em>The Sun</em> doesn&rsquo;t snip out every last shred of potentially offensive content; there&rsquo;d be no humanity left. The magazine promotes tolerance in its own way, by including innocently insensitive humor, as well as criticism about political incorrectness.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Sondra Ahlén<br>Groveland, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
